qx|B05,4-Suit Jacoby Transfers - Transfer to Minors|cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|at|^-
{  Simple Transfer to Minors  }

|fp||CP||CS||at|The transfer to minors can be used for two purposes:|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


AT|

a) to allow responder to bid 3NT with a 6-8 point hand and a 6-card minor suit.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


AT|
  
b) to play in three of a minor with five or fewer points and a 6-card minor.
^-|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


AT|^B@2^Y@3
Most partnerships play Jacoby Transfers for major suits. However, interested players may use Jacoby Transfers for the minors as well. First, let me explain the benefits of transfers in minors.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


AT|

In general, if you have a weak hand with a long suit opposite a strong hand, it is more desirable to play in the weak hand's suit because in that suit, the long cards will take tricks, whereas in another suit it may not be possible to score the low cards in the weak hand's long suit. The only trade off is you have to play at the three level, which is kind of high. However, given a weak hand with seven clubs or diamonds, the trade off is worth it.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


AT|

Some partnerships play 2@S as a transfer to minors. Opener automatically responds 3@C. The partner bidding the transfer passes with clubs or corrects to 3@D. That is easier to play, but not quite as flexible. I recommend you start with this simpler transfer and then progress to the stronger and more flexible version which I will explain next. Let me first show you a few examples of the simple transfer to minors.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


AT|

BTW, all "transfer bids" should be alerted. Further both "accepted" and "rejected" response bids by the NT opener should be alerted as these are additional information available to the partnership that opponents should be aware of. To economize his time, the Movie Maker has not included the alerts in the following examples. Please consider it done in every situation. In all example you are using 2@S to transfer to MINOR(s).|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


